<br>
Yes, it is an art of not getting hit.  But that only applies when things are going the way of the group.  You seem to think that the issue is black and white.  To aggro, or not to aggro.  There are so many situations where aggroing actually becomes appropriate.  And there is so much &quot;in between&quot; area.   It is a complete no-brainer to make the assessment that a wizard who constantly aggros doesn't know what they are doing.  You're not really going out on a limb with that one.  It is a given and doesn't even need to be mentioned.<br>
<br>
The truth of the matter is... people have more respect for a wizard who knows when to take the hit.  I do not have concussion.  I have never used concussion.  I have no need for concussion.  And I can still output as much as the next guy taking my fair share of hits.  In a standard exp group, you do still have hitpoints, so USE them to your advantage.  THAT is where the skill is.  Not just nuking when it seems safely convenient.  And I would say that HELPS my chances to find groups becuase people KNOW I play smart and am willing to take some for the group.  Many others do the same thing.  It isn't a revelation.  Playing smart is not playing YOUR way, or simply playing ONE way.  It is adjusting to every single scenario out there.  And there are many.<br>
<br>
Bottom line is... controling aggro does not mean AVOIDING aggro.  Using it to your advantage is the true skill.<br>
<br>
The point of aggro being a problem is when a tank taunts for several seconds and one nuke pulls it off.  That is simply a logic and mechanics flaw on verants part.  Not a wizard tactical flaw or a question of intelligence.<br>
<br>
Do I think your way is wrong?  No... but it is only ONE way.  And you can't tell me that every single wizard who posts on this site is not &quot;good&quot; because they don't do it your way.  Learning how to avoid aggro was a lesson easily picked up in the early 20's, if not earlier.  I don't think you could find many level 60's out there who have NOT learned the lesson well.<br>
<br>
<br>
Other players don't say &quot;We don't want you in groups because you aggro too much.&quot;  They say &quot;we don't want you because we feel the need can be filled better with [insert class].&quot;  Other classes aren't crying about wizards as a whole because they aggro too much.  Its because they view our group functionality as limited.<br>
<br>
It is not enough to say &quot;aggro spells idiocy.&quot;  But at the same time, I believe that there is a point where a wizard is able to step BEYOND the normal &quot;timing your nukes&quot; strategy and begin to take control of the situation using other means.  NO, I don't mean &quot;nuke til you drop and get group killed in the process.&quot;  But there is a &quot;middle area&quot; not even being addressed here.<br>
<br>
My point on aggro being a problem is simply a mechanical and programming issue.  How a 16 DD spell could aggro the same as Sunstrike in certain situations.  That is not gameplayer intelligence.  That is game development. <p><img src="http://wraithwave.homestead.com/files/Wraith.gif" border="0"><BR><img src="http://wraithwave.homestead.com/files/Wraith2.gif" border="0"><BR><img src="http://wraithwave.homestead.com/files/Wraith3.gif" border="0"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ujacestar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>jacestar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/5/01 2:20 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: absor/agro</span><hr size=1> i completly aggree with wraithwave  ive had this discussion a few times with   50+ wizards on cazicthule  and even a couple times in shout in DL  and every &quot;uber&quot; wizard ive ever talked to has said adaptabilty is the key to being a great wizard.<br>
