This is lame, if anyone else has a opinion to prove me wrong or set me streight on how agro with resists work id love to hear it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/utargonis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Targonis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 146<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/5/01 11:19 am)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: absor/agro</span><hr size=1> It should generate SOME agro, but not anywhere near the amount of agro generated by damage.  The real problem is in the definition of what makes a spell get resisted in the first place.  Did your spell get absorbed by the creature's armor/hide/scales, in which case it might feel it without takeing damage, or does the magical energy just do nothing based on the armor, in which case the mob doesn't feel it.<br>
<br>
That's the issue I have with how resists work, if &quot;shards of ice&quot; have the ability to cut, then that means it's a physical type of damage, and shouldn't be resistable as such.  If you freeze the mob, then yea, that's more of a, &quot;It's getting frostbite&quot; type of thing.  Burning a mob should be the least resistable type of spell for most types of mobs, that along with magic(lightning) for damage. <br>
<br>
Why is root resisted for example?  Root might be dodged, as projections of ground that come up to envelop your feet MIGHT be avoided, but if you have your feet stuck in solid rock, that's NOT something that can be resisted, only avoided, or broken free of.  Atol's Spectral Shackles, how are these NOT going to link the feet of the mob together?  It could be broken, but how do you avoid something like that, it's magic based!  The only thing that might happen would be magical boots/leggings that resist the spell.  If your spell is cast and it says something like, &quot;Projections of rock reach up to grasp the feet of %t, but %t jumps and avoids it&quot;, that would be a hell of a lot better than &quot;%t has resisted.&quot;.  Basically, Verant was very lazy about their reasons for resists, they followed the lame Dungeons and Dragons &quot;Saving Throw&quot; concept, but didn't think about the idea behind it.  If a human, ANY human, ends up in the path of dragon breath, unless there's magical protection, that human is dead.  The only hope is to dodge the effect, or have a complete sphere of resistance around you.<br>
<br>
